			<title>Television New Series: NARCOS (netflix original)</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78113-New-Series-NARCOS-(netflix-original)&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sat, 05 Sep 2015 15:47:59 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Narcos just hit Netflix this past week, August 28th.  
 
I clicked in before I went to bed on Monday evening. I watched the first episode and thought it was superbly well done. Out of the 10 episodes, now, I've watched 3 and a half. It is more than likely a "True Detective" style of mini-series,...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Narcos just hit Netflix this past week, August 28th. <br />
<br />
I clicked in before I went to bed on Monday evening. I watched the first episode and thought it was superbly well done. Out of the 10 episodes, now, I've watched 3 and a half. It is more than likely a &quot;True Detective&quot; style of mini-series, where each season will likely focus on a different drug lord, and appropriately, they went with the one most Americans would name first.  <br />
<br />
Pablo Escobar, the infamous Colombian drug lord is the center of this season. From the very beginning, he is the person whose (real-person) face is seen in the opening credits. The entire narration of the series is done by the primary DEA agent from the United States who got himself involved from the very cornerstones in Miami and started to work his way up to the man himself. <br />
<br />
The story, though narrated by the DEA agent, focuses far less on his personal story, and the rungs in the ladders he had to climb in order to get there, and instead focuses on the story in a manner similar to &quot;The First 48 hours&quot; or &quot;Real ER Stories&quot; that are popular in reality television. The DEA agent narrator, instead, details all the information about Pablo Escobar that you already knew, and plenty you didn't. INcluding his affiliation with Radical Guerilla group, M-19 (and its small amount of history) that you definitely never heard about in the mainstream media. <br />
<br />
The actor who portrays Pablo Escobar looks less like the every-man that Pablo Escobar actually was, and, strangely, looks much more like the Adrian Grenier/Vinny Chase portrayal from Entourage that made up so much of the 4th season of that show. It isn't a distraction, but for those who are familliar with it, will probably grow a little more comfortable with the Pablo Escobar featured in NARCOS because of it - He is portrayed in far more shades of grey than any other previous portrayal, and it does it very, very well. <br />
<br />
I love Colombia. Bogota is one of the most beautiful cities in the world, and at its altitude of nearly 10,000 feet, it has a skyline that is breathtaking, and they did not fall short on its beauty, because they shot nearly every scene of it in actual streets, on actual street corners, in actual buildings where the story transpires in its real history. This is a beautiful colonial world that never gets its story told in modern media the way that it should, and this series <b>does not fail.</b><br />
<br />
By focusing on Bogota, and less of the trafficking that occurred in and around Medellin, the story really makes the shades of grey limitless in its story of how unaffected some regions in Colombia were by the drug corruption that flowed in there from South America (at least in the beginning). <br />
<br />
This is a fantastic work of modern film, and I <i>really</i> hope, that in addition to staying as great as it does in the first 4 episodes, continues on for more than just it as a series, and perhaps brings American Television to learn more about Central and South American history. It touches lightly on several small figureheads of Colombian and South American History, but nowhere in the necessity of the broad strokes that exist in its complete history against the towers that US citizens feel that  their history dwarfs all others on the two continents. <br />
<br />
The supporting actor in the series who plays sort of a sleazy sidekick is done by the same actor who played Oberyn Martell in the Game of Thrones series. No head crushing in this one .... yet.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
