			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Hey-hey! That time of year again! It's amazing how fast the summer goes when the Cubs are winning and you are staring at a 4-8 season for the Iowa Hawkeyes! /puke If a 16% decline in season ticket sales doesn't convince them that it's time for Kirk Ferentz to hang up the headphones maybe playing a home night game in November in front of 30k Minnesota fans because Iowa fans are so fed up with the team will convince them.<br />
<br />
As you can see, I don't have a whole lot of faith in Iowa this fall, but then if you had the misfortune of watching that abortion of a football game they played in last January, you'd be on the same page as me.<br />
<br />
I mean, he threw the kickoff forward!<br />
<br />

<iframe class="restrain" title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/cLL4OBTp-AQ?wmode=opaque" frameborder="0"  allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen  mozallowfullscreen ></iframe>
<br />
<br />
Anyway, time for the teams who actually have a chance to be relevant by October. As for the Big 10, Well you have to go with Ohio State again. They are so far ahead of the rest of the league in talent, coaching, and organization anymore it's just not even fair. They are the Barcelona of college football right now. Alabama was that a few years ago but now we are seeing the beginning of Ohio State's run as the &quot;dynasty&quot;, as much as you get them in college football. I really don't see anyone threatening Ohio State this year. Michigan State can at least play on the same field with them and will surely be in contention for what used to be a BCS bowl. Michigan, while they will be remarkably better, is probably still a couple years away. It takes time to turn programs around. Urban Meyer picked up a team that was already among the best teams in the country so it was easier for him to get them to the next level. The rest of the Big 10, Wisconsin will be good, but not as good as they have been. Minnesota looks like they are reaching the top of an upswing and, why not, I'll pick them to win the <STRIKE>Big 12 North</STRIKE> Big 10 West for the honor of getting slaughtered in the Big 10 championship game by 70 points. Putting all of the marquee teams and all of the recruiting into one division might make sense geographically, but it is destroying the quality of teams in the West. Not sure how long Delaney will keep that up, but then if the money keeps rolling in will anyone notice?<br />
<br />
So, Ohio State, and for my other three I'll go with Alabama, Oregon again, and Baylor getting the invite this year. It will be a controversial decision over Michigan State but since MSU will have lost a close game to Ohio State that will give the one loss Baylor team the nod to face Ohio State in the first round of the playoffs. I'll go with Ohio State and Alabama with Ohio State winning the slugfest for the national championship again.<br />
<br />
Good luck to all this season, me? I'll be watching the Cubs in October and then anxiously await to see who the Blackhawks trade Patrick Kane to for hockey season.</div>

